Most of my services require access to an internal service, and currently I've just repeated "WithRefeference(<internalService>)". This sounds like it could reduce needless boilerplate, and would be inline with how minimal APIs function in aspnetcore.

That said, I have another proposition. How about being able to group annotations together.

```cs
var internalService = builder.AddProject<[...];
var applicationInsights = builder.[...];

var backendStuff = builder.CreateComposable(internalService, applicationInsights);

var backendOne = builder.Add[...]
    .WithReference(backendStuff);

// The former is equivalent to: 
var backendOne = builder.Add[...]
    .WithReference(applicationInsights)
    .WithReference(internalService);

```

This would solve the problem, but would also allow resources to be apart of multiple "groups", which the actual group proposal wouldn't really

@adamint is taking a stab at implementing this in #9425 but I think we should discuss the API approach here a little bit more. This is something simple that you could do today with our existing APIs:

```
var builder = DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder();

var p1 = builder.AddProject<P1>()
       .WithEnvironment("unique", "1") ;

var p2 = builder.AddProject<P2>()
       .WithEnvironment("unique", "2") ;

var p3 = builder.AddProject<P3>()
       .WithEnvironment("unique", "3") ;

AddImportantFooStuff([p1, p2, p3]);

builder.Build().Run();

public static void AddImportantFooStuff(params IResourceWithEnvironment[] resources)
{
  foreach (var resource in resources)
  {
    resource.WithEnvironment("shared", "shared value");
  }
}
```

Grouping implies hierarchy in application of environment variables which isn't always what you want. Further what happens with dynamically injected child resources - do they get placed into the group as well? Do they get the environment variables?

I think we should avoid this for now. I think it would be useful to add a tagging mechanism to the app model where you can do this:

```csharp
var builder = DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder();

var p1 = builder.AddProject<P1>()
       .WithTag("x")
       .WithEnvironment("unique", "1") ;

var p2 = builder.AddProject<P2>()
       .WithTag("x")
       .WithEnvironment("unique", "2") ;

var p3 = builder.AddProject<P3>()
       .WithTag("y")
       .WithEnvironment("unique", "3") ;

builder.Build().Run();
```

Then you could optionally do something like this:

```csharp
var builder = DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder();

var p1 = builder.AddProject<P1>()
       .WithTag("x")
       .WithEnvironment("unique", "1") ;

var p2 = builder.AddProject<P2>()
       .WithTag("x")
       .WithEnvironment("unique", "2") ;

var p3 = builder.AddProject<P3>()
       .WithTag("y")
       .WithEnvironment("unique", "3") ;

builder.Eventing.Subscribe<BeforeResourceStart>((e, ct) => {
  if (e.Resource.HasTag("x"))
  {
    // Do whatever to mutate resource.
  }
});

builder.Build().Run();
```

