```

As for finding out which connection strings exist, if they are annotations they can be iterated the same way as endpoints when running the host.

> > The AddConnectionString method would work if we had access to all the private ReferenceExpressions in the different resources
> 
> You do.

Just a quick glance at https://github.com/dotnet/aspire/blob/main/src/Aspire.Hosting.Azure.PostgreSQL/AzurePostgresFlexibleServerResource.cs

```
internal PostgresServerResource? InnerResource { get; private set; }
internal ParameterResource? UserNameParameter { get; set; }
internal ParameterResource? PasswordParameter { get; set; }
```
So I can't access the InnerResource, which is the container if I use RunAsContainer. I can't access UserName or Password parameters, so I have to get them from outside.

in https://github.com/dotnet/aspire/blob/4cf659537878bd70bcc5035bcd82126ef467ade2/src/Aspire.Hosting.Azure.PostgreSQL/AzurePostgresExtensions.cs#L427 

`var postgres = CreatePostgreSqlFlexibleServer(infrastructure, distributedApplicationBuilder, azureResource.Databases);`

which is then used for the connection strings:

`Value = BicepFunction.Interpolate($"Host={postgres.FullyQualifiedDomainName};[...]`

so now I have to go on the hunt for the ProvisioningResource and PostgresServerResource and my code looks like this:

```
var postgresUser = builder.AddParameter("postgresUser", "postgres", true);
var postgresPassword = builder.AddResource(ParameterResourceBuilderExtensions.CreateDefaultPasswordParameter(builder, "postgresPassword")); // there's probably a nicer way to do this, haven't found it yet

PostgreSqlFlexibleServer? flexibleServer = null;
PostgresServerResource? postgresServer = null;

var postgres = builder.AddAzurePostgresFlexibleServer("postgres")
  .WithPasswordAuthentication(postgresUser, postgresPassword)
  .ConfigureInfrastructure(infra =>
    {
      flexibleServer = infra.GetProvisionableResources()
                                .OfType<PostgreSqlFlexibleServer>()
                                .Single();
    }).RunAsContainer(cfg =>
  {
    postgresServer = cfg.Resource;
    cfg.WithUserName(postgresUser);
    cfg.WithPassword(postgresPassword);
  });

var postgresdb = postgres.AddDatabase("postgresdb");

var pgConn = builder.AddConnectionString("pgconn", postgresServer is null
? ReferenceExpression.Create($"postgres://{postgresUser}:{postgresPassword}@{flexibleServer.FullyQualifiedDomainName}/{postgresdb.Resource.Name}")
: ReferenceExpression.Create($"postgres://{postgresUser}:{postgresPassword}@{postgres.Resource.Name}:{postgresServer!.GetEndpoint("tcp").Port.ToString()}/{postgresdb.Resource.Name}"));
```

only that `flexibleServer.FullyQualifiedDomainName` is a bicep value and can't be used in a ReferenceExpression. So now I have to reverse engineer or somehow hardcode the naming scheme. The endpoint of the postgresServer is also not created at this point so I can't access the port here and there is no ReferenceExpression I've found to just get the port.

For anyone curious, with the suggestion from https://github.com/dotnet/aspire/issues/8034#issuecomment-2833605087 I made a uri-style postgres connection string work, but of course the overall question of multiple connection string formats remains, as this is rather inelegant.

```cs
var postgresUser = builder.AddParameter("postgresUser", "postgres", true);
var pwGenerator = new GenerateParameterDefault { MinLength = 8 };
var postgresPassword = builder.AddParameter("postgresPassword", pwGenerator, secret: true);

ReferenceExpression? hostEndpoint = null;

var postgres = builder.AddAzurePostgresFlexibleServer("postgres")
  .WithPasswordAuthentication(postgresUser, postgresPassword)
  .ConfigureInfrastructure(infra =>
    {
      var flexibleServer = infra.GetProvisionableResources()
                                .OfType<PostgreSqlFlexibleServer>()
                                .Single();
      // Add the host name as an output to the bicep module
      infra.Add(new ProvisioningOutput("hostname", typeof(string))
      {
          Value = flexibleServer.FullyQualifiedDomainName
      });
    })
  .RunAsContainer(cfg =>
  {
    hostEndpoint = ReferenceExpression.Create($"{cfg.Resource.PrimaryEndpoint.Property(EndpointProperty.Host)}:{cfg.Resource.PrimaryEndpoint.Property(EndpointProperty.Port)}");
    cfg.WithUserName(postgresUser);
    cfg.WithPassword(postgresPassword);
  });

hostEndpoint ??= ReferenceExpression.Create($"{postgres.GetOutput("hostname")}");

var pgConn = builder.AddConnectionString("pgconn", ReferenceExpression.Create($"postgres://{postgresUser}:{postgresPassword}@{hostEndpoint}/{postgresdb.Resource.Name}"));
```

