Right, we did not do any work to enable consumption of containers running on a separate machine (not bound to the loopback interface).

@biqas my question here https://github.com/dotnet/aspire/issues/2811#issuecomment-1995986769 was meant to tease out how you are exposing your containers running on the Linux VM to the Windows VM.

I also want to point out that what is supported today (on Mac) is running/debugging Aspire apps via Podman Desktop and VS Code.

This is a really hard problem to solve generally. Today aspire has [a model](https://gist.github.com/davidfowl/b408af870d4b5b54a28bf18bffa127e1) represented with C# code and resources may translate that model into something like a manifest (what is used today for azd and aspirate), docker compose file, or bicep, or cloud formation etc. 

The current assumption is that values (see the value references in the doc) are lazy and translate into external parameters when doing the translation. As an example, if you need to translate an aspire parameter to bicep there's a mapping stored to understand how the model in C# maps to bicep parameters and the runtime can fill those in when executing.

When publishing it's more difficult. Take this example:

Lowercase the input parameter.

```C#
var builder = DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

var param = builder.AddParameter("param1");
var project = builder.AddProject<Projects.Api>("project1")
                     .WithEnvironment("ParamLower", param.Resource.Value.ToLowerInvariant());

builder.Build().Run();
```

This looks simple, but it assumes you can do this all in C#. This may work in run mode, and you'll be able to see the transformation on the input parameter in the "ParamLower" environment variable at runtime. When we translate this into the manifest or any other publishing target, we don't have the value, nor can we lowercase it, we need to store that somewhere.

I see some ways forward here:
- Support a fixed set of transformations. At a minimum make it possible to express the transformation in an inspectable way (there are multiple ways to do this).
- Do "client side evaluation" this requires a runtime before launching various deployment engines/runtimes parameter filling.

