There are a number of different concrete types that all implement `IManifestExpressionProvider` and `IValueProvider` however they don't share a common base type. This makes it difficult to author logic that wants to set an environment variable or similar value to an updated value that includes the existing value, as the custom string interpolation handler requires a single compile-time constant type in order to use the existing value as a token in the interpolated string, e.g.:

```csharp
...
else if (context.ExecutionContext.IsPublishMode)
{
    // WORKAROUND: https://github.com/dotnet/aspire/issues/3749
    // Set ASPNETCORE_HTTP_PORTS to enable listening on the health checks endpoint
    var healthChecksPort = healthChecksEndpoint.Property(EndpointProperty.Port);
    if (context.EnvironmentVariables.TryGetValue(ASPNETCORE_HTTP_PORTS, out var existingValue))
    {
        // Preprend the existing value
        var updatedPorts = existingValue switch
        {
            ReferenceExpression expressionValue => ReferenceExpression.Create($"{expressionValue};{healthChecksPort}"),
            EndpointReferenceExpression endpointExpressionValue => ReferenceExpression.Create($"{endpointExpressionValue};{healthChecksPort}"),
            // Should likely be handling other concrete expression types here but they could be in external packages
            _ => ReferenceExpression.Create($"{existingValue.ToString()};{healthChecksPort}")
        };

        context.EnvironmentVariables[ASPNETCORE_HTTP_PORTS] = updatedPorts;
    }
    else
    {
        context.EnvironmentVariables.Add(ASPNETCORE_HTTP_PORTS, ReferenceExpression.Create($"8080;{healthChecksPort}"));
    }
}
```

We should consider introducing a common base type or changing the existing `ReferenceExpression` type to be the common base type of `EndpointReferenceExpression`, `ConnectionStringReference`, `StackOutputReference`, etc. It might be more complicated than this though as there are non-reference expression types that also implement `IManifestExpressionProvider` and `IValueProvider`. Perhaps we should introduce a new interface that combines `IManifestExpressionProvider` and `IValueProvider`, e.g. `IExpressionValue`, and have all concrete types implement that. Then the above code could change to the following and would properly support any existing value that implements `IExpressionValue`:

```csharp
...
else if (context.ExecutionContext.IsPublishMode)
{
    // WORKAROUND: https://github.com/dotnet/aspire/issues/3749
    // Set ASPNETCORE_HTTP_PORTS to enable listening on the health checks endpoint
    var healthChecksPort = healthChecksEndpoint.Property(EndpointProperty.Port);
    if (context.EnvironmentVariables.TryGetValue(ASPNETCORE_HTTP_PORTS, out var existingValue))
    {
        // Preprend the existing value
        var updatedPorts = existingValue switch
        {
            IExpressionValue expressionValue => ReferenceExpression.Create($"{expressionValue};{healthChecksPort}"),
            _ => ReferenceExpression.Create($"{existingValue.ToString()};{healthChecksPort}")
        };

        context.EnvironmentVariables[ASPNETCORE_HTTP_PORTS] = updatedPorts;
    }
    else
    {
        context.EnvironmentVariables.Add(ASPNETCORE_HTTP_PORTS, ReferenceExpression.Create($"8080;{healthChecksPort}"));
    }
}
```

