Sometime Parameters in the User Secrets secret are being modified to contain `\u0026` instead of `&`.

So this

```json
{
    "Parameters:token": "some=thing&looking=url&like=true"
}
```

is turned into this

```json
{
    "Parameters:token": "some=thing\u0026looking=url\u0026like=true"
}
```

Being used like this:

```chsharp
var builder = DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
var token = builder.AddParameter("token", secret: true);
var sqlServer = builder.AddSqlServer("sql")
    .WithEnvironment("TOKEN", token);
builder.Build().Run();
```

I haven't found the exact cause when this happens.

I just noticed, that I also have a password that suddenly did not work anymore: `P\u002BqMWNzkn*xm1rhXNF5st0`.
So also happening for `\u002B` or `+` character.

VS: Version 17.12.0 Preview 1.0
Aspire 8.2.0 (Could also have been the previous version, as it is hard to determine when it happend)

### Is there an existing issue for this?

- [X] I have searched the existing issues

### Describe the bug

If you call `WithImage` on a resource that already has a tag specified, it ovewrites the existing tag with `latest`.

This is because `WithImage` has an optional parameter with a default value of `"latest"`.
https://github.com/dotnet/aspire/blob/af5fee35d59bb2a802aa0b3e2110623d4e7f4e9b/src/Aspire.Hosting/ContainerResourceBuilderExtensions.cs#L141

### Expected Behavior

Given that I didn't provide a tag to `WithImage()`, I'd expect the container to continue using my existing tag.

### Steps To Reproduce

```cs
[Fact]
    [Fact]
    public void WithImageShouldNotOverrideTag()
    {
        using var builder = TestDistributedApplicationBuilder.Create();
        var redis = builder
            .AddContainer("redis", "original-tag")
            .WithImage("redis-stack");

        var annotation = redis.Resource.Annotations.OfType<ContainerImageAnnotation>().Single();
        Assert.Equal("original-tag", redis.Resource.Annotations.OfType<ContainerImageAnnotation>().Single().Tag);
        Assert.Null(annotation.SHA256);
    }

    [Fact]
    public void WithImageShouldNotOverrideDigest()
    {
        using var builder = TestDistributedApplicationBuilder.Create();
        var redis = builder
            .AddContainer("redis")
            .WithImageSHA256("ffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffff")
            .WithImage("redis-stack");

        var annotation = redis.Resource.Annotations.OfType<ContainerImageAnnotation>().Single();
        Assert.Equal("ffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffff", annotation.SHA256);
        Assert.Null(annotation.Tag);
    }
```

### Exceptions (if any)

```
    Assert.Equal() Failure: Strings differ
           ↓ (pos 0)
Expected: "original-tag"
Actual:   "latest"
           ↑ (pos 0)
```

### .NET Version info

Repro'd against commit af5fee35d59bb2a802aa0b3e2110623d4e7f4e9b (latest `main` at the time of writing)

### Anything else?

One solution to fix this would be to break up `WithImage(string image, string tag = "latest")` into two methods, however this would be a breaking change according to the PublicApi analysers:
```cs
public static IResourceBuilder<T> WithImage<T>(this IResourceBuilder<T> builder, string image) where T : ContainerResource
{
   // Existing implementation
}

public static IResourceBuilder<T> WithImage<T>(this IResourceBuilder<T> builder, string image, string tag = "latest") where T : ContainerResource
  => builder.WithImage(image).WithTag(tag);
```

A side effect of this change is that the `ContainerImageAnnotaiton.Tag` property will now be null for such.  The property already is nullable so consumers should be able to handle this possibility.  This also makes it consistent with `ContainerImageAnnotaiton.Repository` which we leave as null rather than defaulting to `docker.io`.

Fixing this will also provide a partial solution to #4355 as it is the addition of an additional `latest` tag that breaks container references given to `WithImage()`.  (Note, this is only a partial solution to that problem as whilst DCP will start the correct container, the `ContainerResourceAnnotation` is not correctly broken down to it's constituent parts.)  You can see this behaviour as the following will start up the expected container once the tag has been reset to null.

```cs
builder.AddContainer("a1", "mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/aspire-dashboard:8.1", null!);
var x = builder.AddContainer("a2", "mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/aspire-dashboard:8.1")
    .WithImageTag(null!);
```

