You can hide resources by setting the resource state to `KnownResourceStates.Hidden`.  This is used for the Aspire Dashboard which is a resource but doesn't show up.

@KennethHoff For your use case, you can do something like the following to hide the resource once it completes.  The advantage of this over a hidden annotation is that if `pnpm` fails for whatever reason, you'll still be able to see it in the dashboard to investigate the cause, and see why other things may have failed to start.

```cs
var app = appBuilder.AddExecutable("pnpm", "whatever", ".");
appBuilder.Eventing.Subscribe<BeforeStartEvent>((e, c) =>
{
    _ = Task.Run(async () => { 
        var resourceNotificationService = e.Services.GetRequiredService<ResourceNotificationService>();

        await resourceNotificationService.WaitForResourceAsync(app.Resource.Name, x => x.Snapshot.State?.Text == KnownResourceStates.Finished && x.Snapshot.ExitCode == null, c);
        await resourceNotificationService.PublishUpdateAsync(app.Resource, s => s with { State = new(KnownResourceStates.Hidden, null)});
    });
    return Task.CompletedTask;
});
```

