```csharp
  var endpoints = builder.AddProject("endpoints",
  "../../../endpoints/src/Services/Services.csproj")
      .WithEndpoint("http", endpoint => endpoint.Port = ServicesPorts.Endpoints);

  var opApiSync = builder.AddProject("operations-api-sync",
  "../../../operations-api/src/Sync.Services/Sync.Services.csproj")
      .WithEndpoint("http", endpoint => endpoint.Port = ServicesPorts.OpApi);

  var gateway = builder.AddYarp("gateway")
      .WithConfiguration(yarp =>
      {
          yarp.AddRoute(opApiSync);
          yarp.AddRoute("/v3/operations/get-existing-operation", endpoints.GetEndpoint("http"));
      });
```

The YARP gateway (running in a container) cannot proxy requests to the endpoints and opApiSync projects because they're not in the Aspire network. The gateway fails to reach these services.

**Workaround**: I created a separate YARP proxy project that runs on the host network instead of using AddYarp(). This allows the proxy to communicate with localhost services since it runs on the host network rather than in the Aspire container network.

Will this issue be addressed in next version?

We’ve traced this to how **Podman runs containers inside a lightweight VM**:

* Inside the container, `host.containers.internal` resolves to the **Podman VM**, not your physical host.
* To let containers call host-side services, point that hostname at the **VM’s gateway IP** (the host as seen from the VM).
* Also ensure containerized apps **bind to `0.0.0.0`** (not just `localhost`) so traffic arriving through the gateway can reach them.

### Workaround (Windows)

1. Get the gateway IP (the “via” address):

   ```powershell
   wsl -d podman-machine-default -- ip -4 route show default
   ```

   Example output: `default via 172.20.112.1 dev eth0 …` → gateway = `172.20.112.1`.
2. Run containers with:

   ```
   --add-host=host.containers.internal:<gatewayIP>
   ```
3. Ensure services inside containers listen on `0.0.0.0`.

### Workaround (macOS)

1. Get the gateway IP from the Podman VM:

   ```bash
   podman machine ssh podman-machine-default ip -4 route show default
   ```

   Example: `default via 192.168.127.1 dev eth0 …` → gateway = `192.168.127.1`.
2. Run containers with:

   ```
   --add-host=host.containers.internal:<gatewayIP>
   ```
3. Ensure services inside containers listen on `0.0.0.0`.

> Tip: You can make the mapping global by setting `host_containers_internal_ip = "<gatewayIP>"` in `~/.config/containers/containers.conf` (macOS) or `%USERPROFILE%\.config\containers\containers.conf` (Windows).

---

### Networking boundaries

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    C[Container<br/>Service bound to 0.0.0.0] 
    B1[Barrier: Podman VM network bridge]
    VMGW[host.containers.internal<br/>→ 172.20.x.1 gateway]
    B2[Barrier: WSL/Podman VM boundary]
    W[OS Host<br/>Service bound to 0.0.0.0:PORT]

    C -- "requests → host.containers.internal:PORT" --> B1
    B1 --> VMGW
    VMGW -- "forwards to 172.20.x.1" --> B2
    B2 --> W

    classDef barrier fill:#fff,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,stroke-dasharray: 5 3;
    class B1,B2 barrier;
```

---

**Result:** Containers can reliably reach host-side services via `host.containers.internal` on both Windows and macOS, with services inside containers reachable through the Podman VM gateway.

Here's some code you can use to isolate this to the aspire application:

This does change all projects and executables to bind to 0.0.0.0 instead of localhost, so beware of that. It’s needed because when an app only listens on localhost, connections arriving from outside the container (via the Podman VM gateway) will be refused. Binding to 0.0.0.0 ensures the service accepts traffic on all interfaces, including the one bridged through host.containers.internal.

**Security implications:

Binding to 0.0.0.0 makes the service accessible on every network interface inside the container. That means if the container’s port is published (e.g., -p 5000:5000), the service will be reachable from your entire host machine (and potentially your LAN, depending on firewall/NAT settings).

This is generally fine in a local development setup where you control the network and are running against Podman Desktop/WSL.

For production scenarios, you typically wouldn’t want everything listening on all interfaces. Instead, you’d rely on container network isolation, ingress controllers, or reverse proxies to explicitly expose only what’s needed.**

In short: this is a pragmatic development-time workaround to make Podman networking behave consistently on Windows/macOS, but it shouldn’t be treated as a best practice for securing production workloads.


```C#
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

namespace Aspire.Hosting;

/// <summary>
/// Adds runtime adjustments that make containerized services reachable when running on Windows with Podman.
/// <para>
/// Background: On Windows, Podman runs containers inside a lightweight Linux VM. Inside a container the special
/// hostname <c>host.containers.internal</c> resolves to the VM, not the physical Windows host. To allow containers
/// to call services (for example, other projects or tools) on the Windows host we inject an extra host mapping so
/// that <c>host.containers.internal</c> resolves to the VM gateway IP (the "via" address shown by
/// <c>wsl -d podman-machine-default -- ip -4 route show default</c>, e.g. <c>172.20.112.1</c>).
/// </para>
/// <para>
/// We also force all executable/project resources that expose endpoints to bind to <c>0.0.0.0</c>. Some apps bind
/// only to <c>localhost</c> by default; inside the VM that would prevent traffic arriving through the gateway from
/// reaching the service. Setting <see cref="EndpointReference.TargetHost"/> to <c>0.0.0.0</c> ensures they listen on
/// all interfaces.
/// </para>
/// <para>
/// Result: Each container gets an added runtime arg <c>--add-host=host.containers.internal:&lt;gatewayIP&gt;</c> and every
/// discovered endpoint for executable or project resources is updated to listen on all interfaces, making internal
/// calls and cross-container communication reliable.
/// </para>
/// </summary>
public static class ContainerVMGatewayFixupExtensions
{

    /// <summary>
    /// Registers an event subscription that, just before the distributed application starts, iterates all resources and:
    /// <list type="number">
    /// <item><description>Adds a host mapping so <c>host.containers.internal</c> resolves to the provided <paramref name="gatewayIP"/> for every container resource.</description></item>
    /// <item><description>Ensures executable and project resources' endpoints listen on <c>0.0.0.0</c> instead of only localhost.</description></item>
    /// </list>
    /// Obtain <paramref name="gatewayIP"/> on Windows + Podman by running:
    /// <code>wsl -d podman-machine-default -- ip -4 route show default</code>
    /// and taking the <c>via</c> address (e.g. <c>172.20.112.1</c>).
    /// </summary>
    /// <param name="builder">The distributed application builder.</param>
    /// <param name="gatewayIP">Gateway IP (the VM's default route "via" IP) to map to <c>host.containers.internal</c>.</param>
    /// <returns>The same <see cref="IDistributedApplicationBuilder"/> for chaining.</returns>
    public static IDistributedApplicationBuilder AddGatewayFixups(this IDistributedApplicationBuilder builder, string? gatewayIP = null)
    {
        // Only apply these fixups during an actual run (skip for operations like 'generate', 'publish', etc.).
        if (!builder.ExecutionContext.IsRunMode)
        {
            return builder;
        }

        builder.Eventing.Subscribe<BeforeStartEvent>((e, ct) =>
        {
            var hostLogger = e.Services.GetRequiredService<ILoggerFactory>().CreateLogger("PodmanGatewayFixup");
            var gatewayIPTask = gatewayIP is null
                ? TryResolvePodmanGatewayIpAsync(hostLogger, ct)
                : Task.FromResult<string?>(gatewayIP);

            var rls = e.Services.GetRequiredService<ResourceLoggerService>();

            foreach (var r in e.Model.Resources)
            {
                // 1. For every container resource, inject a host alias so inside the container
                //    'host.containers.internal' resolves to the Podman VM gateway IP.
                if (r.IsContainer())
                {
                    r.Annotations.Add(new ContainerRuntimeArgsCallbackAnnotation(async args =>
                    {
                        var logger = rls.GetLogger(r);

                        logger.LogDebug("Resolving Podman gateway IP for container resource '{ResourceName}'.", r.Name);

                        var gatewayIP = await gatewayIPTask;

                        if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(gatewayIP))
                        {
                            return;
                        }

                        logger.LogInformation("Adding host mapping for host.containers.internal (gateway IP: {GatewayIP})", gatewayIP);

                        // Add the mapping so inside the container 'host.containers.internal' resolves to the Podman VM gateway IP.
                        args.Add($"--add-host=host.containers.internal:{gatewayIP}");
                    }));
                }

                // We only adjust endpoints for executable or project resources (those that can host network services).
                if (r is not ExecutableResource and not ProjectResource) continue;

                // 2. Force endpoints to bind on all interfaces so traffic from outside the container/VM can reach them.
                if (r.TryGetEndpoints(out var endpoints))
                {
                    foreach (var ep in endpoints)
                    {
                        // Setting TargetHost to 0.0.0.0 ensures the underlying process doesn't just listen on localhost.
                        ep.TargetHost = "0.0.0.0";
                    }
                }
            }

            return Task.CompletedTask;
        });

        return builder;
    }

    // Attempts to resolve the Podman VM gateway IP address by invoking WSL.
    // Returns null if the command fails, Podman machine is absent, or parsing fails.
    private static async Task<string?> TryResolvePodmanGatewayIpAsync(ILogger logger, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        try
        {
            logger.LogDebug("Attempting to resolve Podman gateway IP (OS: {OS})", Environment.OSVersion.Platform);

            System.Diagnostics.ProcessStartInfo psi;
            if (OperatingSystem.IsWindows())
            {
                // Windows: use WSL to execute inside the Podman machine
                psi = new System.Diagnostics.ProcessStartInfo
                {
                    FileName = "wsl.exe",
                    ArgumentList = { "-d", "podman-machine-default", "--", "ip", "-4", "route", "show", "default" },
                    RedirectStandardOutput = true,
                    RedirectStandardError = true,
                    UseShellExecute = false,
                    CreateNoWindow = true
                };
            }
            else if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
            {
                // macOS: use the Podman CLI to run the command inside the VM via ssh
                psi = new System.Diagnostics.ProcessStartInfo
                {
                    FileName = "podman",
                    ArgumentList = { "machine", "ssh", "podman-machine-default", "ip", "-4", "route", "show", "default" },
                    RedirectStandardOutput = true,
                    RedirectStandardError = true,
                    UseShellExecute = false,
                    CreateNoWindow = true
                };
            }
            else
            {
                logger.LogDebug("Unsupported OS for automatic Podman gateway resolution. Skipping.");
                return null;
            }

            using var proc = System.Diagnostics.Process.Start(psi);
            if (proc is null)
            {
                logger.LogWarning("Failed to start process for gateway resolution (FileName: {FileName}).", psi.FileName);
                return null;
            }

            using var timeoutCts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(cancellationToken);
            timeoutCts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10));

            var stdOutTask = proc.StandardOutput.ReadToEndAsync();
            var stdErrTask = proc.StandardError.ReadToEndAsync();

            try
            {
                await proc.WaitForExitAsync(timeoutCts.Token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException)
            {
                try { proc.Kill(entireProcessTree: true); } catch { /* ignore */ }
                logger.LogWarning("Gateway resolution command timed out (FileName: {FileName}).", psi.FileName);
                return null;
            }

            string output = await stdOutTask;
            string error = await stdErrTask;

            if (proc.ExitCode != 0)
            {
                logger.LogWarning("Gateway resolution command exited with code {ExitCode}. stderr: {StdErr}", proc.ExitCode, error);
                return null;
            }

            if (string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(output))
            {
                logger.LogWarning("Gateway resolution command produced empty output.");
                return null;
            }

            logger.LogTrace("Raw gateway resolution output: {Output}", output);

            var lines = output.Split('\n', '\r', StringSplitOptions.RemoveEmptyEntries | StringSplitOptions.TrimEntries);
            foreach (var line in lines)
            {
                var parts = line.Split(' ', StringSplitOptions.RemoveEmptyEntries | StringSplitOptions.TrimEntries);
                for (int i = 0; i < parts.Length - 1; i++)
                {
                    if (string.Equals(parts[i], "via", StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase))
                    {
                        var candidate = parts[i + 1];
                        if (System.Net.IPAddress.TryParse(candidate, out var ip) && ip.AddressFamily == System.Net.Sockets.AddressFamily.InterNetwork)
                        {
                            logger.LogDebug("Resolved Podman gateway IP: {Candidate}", candidate);
                            return candidate;
                        }
                    }
                }
            }

            logger.LogWarning("No IPv4 address found after 'via' in gateway resolution output.");
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            logger.LogError(ex, "Exception while resolving Podman gateway IP.");
        }
        return null;
    }
}
```

