>  So either Aspire app host needs to somehow learn what dotnet CLI version is available and change the launch options used accordingly

Hmm we should be able to test what version of the .NET CLI will be used before we dispatch the call to `dotnet run`, via a `dotnet --version` call or similar.

@karolz-ms just to clarify, when you say .NET 9.1, do you mean .NET SDK/CLI 9.0.200, or some other version?

So seems we've ruled out using temp with stable paths names, which leaves the following options:

- Storing files in the app's /bin directory
- Storing files in user secrets directory
- Storing files in the user profile directory

For using the app's /bin directory, while a `git clean` would remove them, a `dotnet clean` would not as the files aren't tracked by the build. I'd like us to avoid adding files to the artifacts or intermediate output directories that aren't correctly tracked by the build as I find it super annoying when `dotnet clean` isn't enough to reset relevant state.

Storing non-secret stuff in the user secrets directory just seems confusing.

So I vote for standardizing on storing stable files like this (those intended to be re-used across launches) in `~/.aspire/`, with the directory being based on the app host name and path hash, e.g.:

```csharp
var appName = Sanitize(builder.Environment.ApplicationName).ToLowerInvariant();
var appNameHash = builder.Configuration["AppHost:Sha256"]![..10].ToLowerInvariant();
var dirName = $"{appName}.{appNameHash}";
var dirPath = Path.Combine(Environment.GetFolderPath(Environment.SpecialFolder.UserProfile), ".aspire", dirName);
// Results in path like: `~/.aspire/my_aspireapp.apphost.236f2386i0`
```

In cases where the file needs to be updated based on content changes, the file name should include a hash based on the relevant content (to @sebastienros' point), e.g. `~/.aspire/my_aspireapp.apphost.236f2386i0/some-content-asdlkjasdoierjoaisdj.xxx`

