Another idea is to introduce a new method `WithDependency` that combines referencing and waiting for another resource in a single call:

```csharp
public static IResourceBuilder<TDestination> WithDependency<TSource, TDestination>(this IResourceBuilder<TDestination> builder, IResourceBuilder<TSource>, WaitBehavior? waitBehavior = null)
    where TSource : IReferenceable<TSource, TDestination>, IResourceWithWaitSupport
{
    TSource.ProcessReference(source, builder);
    return builder.WaitFor(source, waitBehavior);
}
```

This would still require the work to introduce `IReferenceable<TSource, TDestination>` and ensuring any resources with custom reference logic get updated to implement this interface, e.g. `QdrantServerResource`, and would be limited to use with only other resources as only other resources can be waited for. And of course it introduces a new concept of "dependency" which combines two existing concepts of "reference" and "wait for". There would still be cases where one needs to know to call `WithReference` instead of `WithDependency` to wire up service discovery, e.g. for `EndpointReference` and `OrleansService`.

This could be relaxed though by having another overload that doesn't enforce the `IResourceWithWaitSupport` in the generic type constraint but rather makes it a runtime check and only performing the `WaitFor` call if the passed `TSource` implements `IResourceWithWaitSupport`. The overload with the `waitBehavior` argument would still have the generic type constraing, e.g.:

```csharp
public static IResourceBuilder<TDestination> WithDependency<TSource, TDestination>(this IResourceBuilder<TDestination> builder, IResourceBuilder<TSource>)
    where TSource : IReferenceable<TSource, TDestination>
{
    TSource.ProcessReference(source, builder);
    return TSource is IResourceWithWaitSupport waitable ? builder.WaitFor(waitable) : builder;
}

public static IResourceBuilder<TDestination> WithDependency<TSource, TDestination>(this IResourceBuilder<TDestination> builder, IResourceBuilder<TSource>, WaitBehavior waitBehavior)
    where TSource : IReferenceable<TSource, TDestination>, IResourceWithWaitSupport
{
    TSource.ProcessReference(source, builder);
    return builder.WaitFor(source, waitBehavior);
}
```

