I have been experimenting with the current `AppHost.cs` setup over the past few days and would like to share some insights.

## This is what I played with:

```csharp
#!/usr/bin/env dotnet

#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk
#:sdk Aspire.AppHost.Sdk@9.3.1

#:property PublishAot=false

#:package Aspire.Hosting.AppHost@9.3.1
#:package Aspire.Hosting.PostgreSQL@9.*

#:project Api/Api.csproj

var builder = DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Required settings
builder.Configuration["ASPNETCORE_ENVIRONMENT"] ??= "Development";
builder.Configuration["ASPIRE_DASHBOARD_OTLP_ENDPOINT_URL"] ??= "http://localhost:4317";
builder.Configuration["ASPIRE_RESOURCE_SERVICE_ENDPOINT_URL"] ??= "http://localhost:5001";

// Optional settings to improve local development experience
builder.Configuration["ASPIRE_ALLOW_UNSECURED_TRANSPORT"] ??= "true";
builder.Configuration["ASPNETCORE_URLS"] ??= "http://localhost:5003";

builder.Configuration["Logging:LogLevel:Default"] ??= "Information";
builder.Configuration["Logging:LogLevel:Aspire.Hosting.Dcp"] ??= "Warning";
builder.Configuration["Logging:LogLevel:Microsoft.AspNetCore"] ??= "Warning";

var postgres = builder.AddPostgres("postgres")
                      .WithLifetime(ContainerLifetime.Persistent);

var postgresdb = postgres.AddDatabase("db");

var migration = builder.AddCSharpScript("api-db-migration", "Api.Db.Migration.cs")
                       .WithParentRelationship(postgres)
                       .WithReference(postgresdb)
                       .WaitFor(postgresdb);

var api = builder.AddProject<Projects.Api>("api")
                 .WithReference(postgresdb)
                 .WaitFor(postgresdb);

builder.Build().Run();

public static class CSFileExtensions
{
    public static IResourceBuilder<CsharpFileResource> AddCSharpScript(this IDistributedApplicationBuilder builder, string name, string filePath)
    {
        return builder.AddResource(new CsharpFileResource(name, Environment.CurrentDirectory))
                      .WithArgs("run", filePath)
                      .WithEnvironment("OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT", builder.Configuration["ASPIRE_DASHBOARD_OTLP_ENDPOINT_URL"])
                      .WithEnvironment("OTEL_SERVICE_NAME", name);
    }
}

public class CsharpFileResource(string name, string workingDirectory) : ExecutableResource(name, "dotnet", workingDirectory);
```

## Findings

1. Currently, when running `dotnet run AppHost.cs` or `dotnet AppHost.cs`, the project is compiled with AOT, which leads to errors in AppHost. Therefore, you must explicitly set `#:property PublishAot=false`. This could be implied by the `Aspire.AppHost.Sdk` to avoid confusion for developers who may not be aware of this requirement.
2. The following configuration logic could ideally be provided as defaults by the `DistributedApplicationBuilder` itself. This would streamline local development and reduce boilerplate, allowing developers to focus on application-specific settings rather than repeatedly specifying common environment and logging options:
   ```csharp
    // Required settings
    builder.Configuration["ASPNETCORE_ENVIRONMENT"] ??= "Development";
    builder.Configuration["ASPIRE_DASHBOARD_OTLP_ENDPOINT_URL"] ??= "http://localhost:4317";
    builder.Configuration["ASPIRE_RESOURCE_SERVICE_ENDPOINT_URL"] ??= "http://localhost:5001";

    // Optional settings to improve local development experience
    builder.Configuration["ASPIRE_ALLOW_UNSECURED_TRANSPORT"] ??= "true";
    builder.Configuration["ASPNETCORE_URLS"] ??= "http://localhost:5003";

    builder.Configuration["Logging:LogLevel:Default"] ??= "Information";
    builder.Configuration["Logging:LogLevel:Aspire.Hosting.Dcp"] ??= "Warning";
    builder.Configuration["Logging:LogLevel:Microsoft.AspNetCore"] ??= "Warning";
   ```
3. When using `#:sdk Aspire.AppHost.Sdk@9.3.1`, you must also explicitly specify `#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk` because `Aspire.AppHost.Sdk` does not implicitly include the .NET SDK. This can be confusing, as one might expect the AppHost SDK to bring all required dependencies automatically. In general, it would be beneficial if the AppHost SDK could automatically include the necessary .NET SDK and other common dependencies like `Aspire.Hosting.AppHost` to reduce the need for manual configuration in the project file.

## Conclusion

With the introduction of a dedicated Aspire SDK alias such as `Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Aspire`, similar to established SDKs like `Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Web` or `Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Worker`, the setup process could be greatly simplified. This would enable developers to focus on building application features rather than managing environment configuration, resulting in a more streamlined and developer-friendly experience.

One open question remains: Would the release cycle of Aspire, with such an integration, then be directly tied to the .NET version, similar to the other SDKs?

A more streamlined configuration could look like this:

```csharp
#!/usr/bin/env dotnet

#:sdk Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Aspire // Could this be versioned like `Microsoft.NET.Sdk.Aspire@9.3.1`?

#:package Aspire.Hosting.PostgreSQL@9.*
#:project Api/Api.csproj

var builder = DistributedApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

var postgres = builder.AddPostgres("postgres")
                      .WithLifetime(ContainerLifetime.Persistent);

var postgresdb = postgres.AddDatabase("db");

var migration = builder.AddCSharpScript("api-db-migration", "Api.Db.Migration.cs")
                       .WithParentRelationship(postgres)
                       .WithReference(postgresdb)
                       .WaitFor(postgresdb);

var api = builder.AddProject<Projects.Api>("api")
                 .WithReference(postgresdb)
                 .WaitFor(postgresdb);

builder.Build().Run();
```

