Ok, so, big picture. Aspire provides a ready-to-run development environment from the clone. Neat. The development logic is not that far off from my production setup. (In this scenario, "production" is a Raspberry Pi 5, 4-node, Docker swarm cluster with hyper-converged storage for bonus points) (Believe it or not, I have all the capacity I need for my initial needs.) Imagine my excitement when Docker Compose publishing became available.  (Except swarm compose is slightly different (tangent another day)) I could _theoretically_ automate generating the Docker Compose as well. (Before, I would have to generate a manifest and then use Aspir8 to achieve the same thing). And then you tease me with this _deploy_ command on the Aspire CLI, suggesting that I could put all of the logic, including pushing built images to where they need to be, in my Aspire project and never have to touch the compose file again.
The last thing that I need to add is copying my compose and secrets to their swarm storage where I can then execute the stack command (I don't actually need to do this precisely, I could deploy the stack directly from my development machine, but then I'll be figuring into the aspire project as well(one shiny toy at a time please))

The reality is not far off from what I described above, but there are some pain points to be resolved.
- Docker Compose output is not compatible with Swarm out of the box. Yes, swarm can (noisily) ignore specific keys, but others, like the long format of `depends_on`, are incompatible with swarm. Swarm expects a list of strings.
- Deployment labels we've discussed and resolved
- And I'm forced to define volume mapping with functional paths that are platform-specific to my Windows machine, when ultimately they need to be Linux paths. I haven't looked into this one yet, but I'm sure I can just override the volume mappings in the compose context instead of relying on the `ContainerMountAnnotation`
- When you look at my samples, some of the hoops I jumped through were because I cannot use a .env file in a stack deploy. (yes, there are tricks to get around this, but if I don't have to use the `.env`, that's even better)

My current workaround involves using a static `docker-compose.deploy.yaml` (essentially an override) to maintain my "corrections" to the output file and deploy them together. So my goal is to no longer need that second file.

