## Background and Motivation

Aspire currently supports parent-child relationships for resources, but the propagation of events and lifecycle state from parent to child is either implicit or tied to relationship type. This can be ambiguous for complex scenarios where developers need fine-grained control over which aspects of behavior are inherited. Explicitly declaring what is inherited (state, events, or both) improves clarity, makes orchestration predictable, and allows for future extension.

## Proposed API

```csharp
namespace Aspire.Hosting.ApplicationModel;

[Flags]
public enum InheritedBehaviorOptions
{
    None = 0,
    State = 1 << 0,
    Events = 1 << 1,
    All = State | Events
}

public sealed record InheritedBehaviorAnnotation(InheritedBehaviorOptions Options) : IResourceAnnotation
{
    public bool InheritState => (Options & InheritedBehaviorOptions.State) != 0;
    public bool InheritEvents => (Options & InheritedBehaviorOptions.Events) != 0;
}

public static class InheritedBehaviorAnnotationExtensions
{
    public static IResourceBuilder<T> WithInheritedBehavior<T>(this IResourceBuilder<T> builder, InheritedBehaviorOptions options) where T : IResource
    {
        builder.WithAnnotation(new InheritedBehaviorAnnotation(options));
        return builder;
    }
}
```

## Usage Examples

```csharp
// Child that inherits both state and events from parent
builder.AddContainer("sidecar", "image")
    .WithParentRelationship(parent)
    .WithInheritedBehavior(InheritedBehaviorOptions.All);

// Child that only inherits events
builder.AddContainer("diagnostics", "diag-image")
    .WithParentRelationship(parent)
    .WithInheritedBehavior(InheritedBehaviorOptions.Events);

// Child that inherits nothing
builder.AddContainer("independent", "indep-image")
    .WithParentRelationship(parent)
    .WithInheritedBehavior(InheritedBehaviorOptions.None);
```

## Alternative Designs

- Previous model used ParentChildPropagationOptions/ParentChildBehaviorAnnotation with several convenience extension methods. This proposal simplifies the API and uses clearer naming.
- Could be done with attributes on the relationship itself, but an annotation is more flexible and matches existing Aspire extensibility patterns.

## Risks

- Breaking change for projects using the old API names (ParentChildPropagationOptions, etc.) and extension methods (PropagateAllFromParent, etc.).
- Requires migration for consumers of removed/renamed methods.
- Orchestrator logic will need to be updated to recognize the new annotation.
